{"insight":"Before judging truth, hear the sentence's purpose","publicTitle":"Before Silence Becomes Certainty","plainSummary":"After silence, ask what a sentence is doing before making it a judgment about truth or a person.","atAGlance":"Deep quiet can leave people hungry for a final answer. Some sentences guide practice, some warn against pride, some report a change, and some state a belief. Confusion begins when we treat them all as proof. Slow naming can protect truth and protect people from harsh private judgments.","keyPoints":["Meaning changes when a sentence guides, warns, reports, or claims.","A rushed verdict can turn quiet into pride or self-accusation.","Test whether readers can agree on what each sentence is doing."],"match":["first ask what the words do"],"tags":["discernment","silence","practice","humility"]}
